04279nam a22006015i 9780823291830DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232918307 a10.1515/97808232918302doi  a(DE-B1597)566132  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0220002bisacsh1 aCrockett, Clayton, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInterstices of the Sublime :bTheology and Psychoanalytic Theory /cClayton Crockett. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. On Sublimation -- t2. We Are All Mad -- t3. Desiring the Thing -- t4. Foreclosing God -- t5. Anxiety and the S(ub)lime Body of God -- t6. Ages of the World and Creation ex Nihilo, Part I -- t7. Ages of the World and Creation ex Nihilo, Part II -- t8. God Without Being (God) -- t9. Expressing the Real -- t10. Processing the Real -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tPerspectives in Continental Philosophy Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInterstices of the Sublime represents a powerful theological engagement with psychoanalytic theory in Freud, Lacan, Kristeva and Zizek, as well as major expressions of contemporary Continental philosophy, including Deleuze, Derrida, Marion, and Badiou. Through creative and constructive psycho-theological readings of topics such as sublimation, schizophrenia, God, and creation ex nihilo, this book contributes to a new form of radical theological thinking that is deeply involved in the world. Here the idea of the Kantian sublime is read into Freud and Lacan, and compared with sublimation. The sublime refers to a conflict of the Kantian faculties of reason and imagination, and involves the attempt to represent what is intrinsically unrepresentable. Sublimation, by contrast, involves the expression and partial satisfaction of primal desires in culturally acceptable terms. The sublime is negatively expressed in sublimation, because it is both the "source" of sublimation as well as that which resists being sublimated. That is, the Freudian sublime is related to the process of sublimation, but it also distorts or disrupts sublimation, and invokes what Lacan calls the Real. The effects of the sublime are not just psychoanalytic but, importantly, theological, because the sublime is the main form that "God" takes in the modern world. A radical postmodern theology attends to the workings of the sublime in our thinking and living, and provides resources to understand the complexity of reality. This book is one of the first sustained theological readings of Lacan in English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291830423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823291830/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK